  { deck:8, q:"A koala sleeping up to 18 hours a day conserves energy from its low-nutrient diet. This is a:", opts:["Structural adaptation","Physiological adaptation","Behavioural adaptation","Genetic mutation"], ans:2 },
  { deck:8, q:"What type of adaptation involves the way an organism's body chemistry or internal processes work?", opts:["Structural","Behavioural","Physiological","Ecological"], ans:2 },
  { deck:8, q:"The thorny devil lizard absorbs water through channels in its skin. This is a:", opts:["Behavioural adaptation to a desert environment","Structural adaptation to an alpine environment","Physiological adaptation to an arid environment","Learning behaviour"], ans:2 },
  { deck:8, q:"A red kangaroo licks its forearms when overheated. The saliva evaporates and cools the blood. This is a:", opts:["Structural adaptation","Physiological adaptation","Behavioural adaptation for thermoregulation","Sign of illness"], ans:2 },
  { deck:8, q:"Which feature of a mountain pygmy possum is an adaptation to Victoria's alpine environment?", opts:["Large bright colours to attract mates","Hibernating through winter to survive food scarcity and cold","Growing larger to compete with other species","Having stripes for camouflage in tropical forest"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"The platypus has a bill with electroreceptors that detect electrical signals from prey in murky water. This is an example of a:", opts:["Physiological adaptation to aquatic foraging","Behavioural adaptation for courtship","Structural adaptation for running","Learning behaviour"], ans:0 },
  { deck:8, q:"Adaptations arise through the process of:", opts:["Individual learning","Natural selection — organisms with beneficial traits survive and reproduce more","Artificial selection only","Random chance during an organism's lifetime"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"Which of the following is NOT an adaptation?", opts:["A wombat's backwards-facing pouch (keeping soil out when digging)","A student learning to ride a bicycle","Kangaroo fur that reflects sunlight","The platypus's webbed feet for swimming"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"Wurundjeri-Woiwurrung people have detailed knowledge of when and where animals are found, including their seasonal behaviours. This knowledge reflects an understanding of:", opts:["Random animal movements","Behavioural adaptations — animals respond to seasonal changes in predictable ways","Non-living factors only","Adaptations that only occur in captivity"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"The eucalyptus tree's thick, fire-resistant bark is an adaptation to:", opts:["Cold, wet alpine environments","A fire-prone Australian landscape","Salt water immersion","Desert drought only"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"Which animal is BEST adapted to surviving in Victoria's dry sclerophyll woodlands?", opts:["A polar bear","A tropical toucan","A koala — specialised to eat toxic eucalyptus leaves","A deep-sea anglerfish"], ans:2 },
  { deck:8, q:"Why do organisms in the same ecosystem often have similar adaptations?", opts:["They learned from each other","They face the same environmental challenges (climate, predators, food availability)","They are all the same species","They share the same diet"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"A cactus has thick, waxy skin and stores water in its stem. These are adaptations to:", opts:["Cold, wet conditions","Arid conditions with low rainfall","Deep-sea pressure","Tropical humidity"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"In alpine ecosystems, many plants grow low to the ground. This adaptation helps them:", opts:["Compete for light with taller plants","Avoid being flattened by snow and reduce heat loss in cold, windy conditions","Absorb more rainfall","Avoid being eaten by kangaroos"], ans:1 },
  { deck:8, q:"Which of the following is the best definition of a BEHAVIOURAL adaptation?", opts:["A physical feature that helps survival","A change in body chemistry that helps survival","An action or pattern of behaviour that helps an organism survive and reproduce","A trait passed to offspring through DNA"], ans:2 },
  { deck:8, q:"The sugar glider has a thin membrane of skin between its limbs that allows it to glide between trees. This is best described as:", opts:["A physiological adaptation","A behavioural adaptation","A structural adaptation enabling it to exploit a canopy habitat","A learned behaviour"], ans:2 },

  /* ── DECK 9: Introduced Species ────────────────────────────── */
  { deck:9, q:"What is a NATIVE species?", opts:["A species that was deliberately introduced to Australia","A species that evolved in Australia and has always lived there","Any animal found on a farm","A species that is endangered"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"What is an INTRODUCED (exotic) species?", opts:["A species that evolved in Australia","A species brought to a new region (accidentally or deliberately) where it did not naturally occur","Any predator","A species that is beneficial to farmers"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"Which of the following is an example of a species INTRODUCED to Australia that has become invasive?", opts:["The eastern quoll","The red-necked wallaby","The European rabbit","The platypus"], ans:2 },
  { deck:9, q:"European rabbits were introduced to Victoria in the 1850s. What was a major impact on native ecosystems?", opts:["They improved soil quality everywhere","They overgazed vegetation, causing soil erosion and reducing food and habitat for native species","They helped native plants spread","They reduced invasive weeds"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"The cane toad was introduced to Queensland in 1935 to control sugar cane beetles. Why did this become an ecological problem?", opts:["Cane toads ate too many beetles","Cane toads spread disease in cane fields","Cane toads are toxic to native predators that try to eat them and have spread beyond Queensland","Cane toads are too small to affect the ecosystem"], ans:2 },
  { deck:9, q:"Feral cats kill an estimated 1.5 billion native animals in Australia each year. They are MOST damaging because:", opts:["Native prey has not evolved with this predator and has no defences","Cats are smaller than native predators","Cats only hunt introduced species","Native animals have strong defences against cats"], ans:0 },
  { deck:9, q:"Which introduced plant species is a major pest in Victorian grasslands, outcompeting native wildflowers?", opts:["Kangaroo paw","Wattle","Prickly pear","Patterson's curse (Paterson's curse / Salvation Jane)"], ans:3 },
  { deck:9, q:"Why do introduced species often spread rapidly in a new environment?", opts:["They are always larger than native species","They may have no natural predators, parasites, or competitors in the new environment","They grow faster in captivity","They always have better adaptations than native species"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"What term describes a species that spreads rapidly in a new environment and causes ecological harm?", opts:["Exotic species","Keystone species","Invasive species","Endemic species"], ans:2 },
  { deck:9, q:"Varroa mite is a parasite introduced to Australia that threatens honey bee populations. This demonstrates that introduced species can harm ecosystems by:", opts:["Being too small to cause damage","Introducing disease and parasites that native species have no resistance to","Improving food webs","Increasing biodiversity"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"Prior to European colonisation, Wurundjeri-Woiwurrung people managed Country in ways that maintained balance between species. The introduction of rabbits, foxes, and hard-hoofed livestock after colonisation led to:", opts:["Improved biodiversity","Little change to Victorian ecosystems","Severe disruption to ecosystems and loss of native species that Country had supported for millennia","Beneficial soil improvement"], ans:2 },
  { deck:9, q:"The red fox was introduced to Australia for recreational hunting. Its most serious impact has been:", opts:["Competing with other foxes","Preying heavily on ground-nesting birds and small mammals, contributing to species extinctions","Improving pest insect control","Spreading only in urban areas"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"Myxomatosis is a viral disease used as a BIOLOGICAL CONTROL method for rabbits. What is biological control?", opts:["Using chemicals to kill pests","Using another organism (disease, predator, or parasite) to reduce pest numbers","Trapping animals by hand","Building fences around farms"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"Why can it be difficult to eradicate an introduced species once established?", opts:["Scientists do not know they are there","They reproduce rapidly, spread widely, and may have no natural controls in the new environment","They are protected by law everywhere","They only live in small areas"], ans:1 },
  { deck:9, q:"Which statement best describes the impact of introduced species on Australian biodiversity?", opts:["They have no impact on biodiversity","They have increased biodiversity by adding new species","They are one of the leading causes of species extinction and biodiversity loss in Australia","They only affect plant species"], ans:2 },
  { deck:9, q:"European blackberries are an invasive plant in Victoria. They crowd out native plants. Which ecosystem service is MOST directly disrupted?", opts:["Water filtration","Pollination","Habitat and food provision for native animals that relied on native plants","Carbon storage"], ans:2 },
  { deck:9, q:"What is an 'endemic' species?", opts:["A species found only in one specific region and nowhere else naturally","A species introduced from another country","A species that is common worldwide","A species that has become extinct"], ans:0 },
  { deck:9, q:"The introduction of the common starling to Australia has negatively affected native hollow-nesting birds. Which of the following explains this?", opts:["Starlings eat birds","Starlings compete for nesting hollows that native species like parrots need","Starlings pollute water","Starlings are predators of native birds"], ans:1 },

  /* ── DECK 10: Human Impacts on Ecosystems ──────────────────── */
  { deck:10, q:"Which human activity is considered the GREATEST cause of biodiversity loss worldwide?", opts:["Overhunting","Habitat loss and destruction","Water pollution","Noise pollution"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Deforestation means:", opts:["Planting more trees","Clearing forest land, usually for agriculture or development","Studying forest ecosystems","Watering forest trees"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"How does land clearing for agriculture affect native animals?", opts:["It provides more food for native animals","It destroys habitat, reducing food and shelter and fragmenting populations","It has no effect on native animals","It only affects insects"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"What is 'habitat fragmentation'?", opts:["When a habitat is completely destroyed","When a large habitat is broken into smaller, isolated patches","When two habitats merge together","When a new habitat is created"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Plastic pollution in Port Phillip Bay can harm marine animals. Which impact is MOST direct?", opts:["Reducing water temperature","Animals ingesting or becoming entangled in plastic","Increasing photosynthesis in seagrass","Reducing salt content"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Which of the following is a consequence of climate change on Victorian ecosystems?", opts:["More stable rainfall patterns","Longer, more intense bushfire seasons threatening many species","Cooler average temperatures","No change to species ranges"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Colony collapse disorder — where worker bees abandon their hives — is linked to:", opts:["Bees evolving new behaviours","Pesticide exposure, habitat loss, introduced parasites (Varroa mite), and monocropping stress","Natural seasonal cycles only","Too many native flowers"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Monocropping means growing a single crop species across a large area. Why is this harmful to bees?", opts:["Single crops produce too much nectar","Bees need a variety of food sources; monocrops provide limited nutrition and flower for only a short period","Monocrops always use pesticides","Bees prefer forest habitats"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Pesticides are chemicals used to kill pest insects. What is an unintended consequence of pesticide use on ecosystems?", opts:["They only kill the targeted pests","They can also kill or harm non-target organisms, including pollinators, predators, and soil organisms","They improve soil biodiversity","They have no effect on water quality"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"What is EUTROPHICATION?", opts:["A process where deserts form","When excess nutrients (often from fertiliser runoff) cause rapid algae growth in water, depleting oxygen and killing aquatic life","The natural aging of a lake","A type of drought"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Urban expansion in Melbourne has reduced natural habitat for species like the southern brown bandicoot. This is an example of:", opts:["Introduced species impact","Pollution","Habitat loss due to urbanisation","Overexploitation"], ans:2 },
  { deck:10, q:"Traditional Wurundjeri-Woiwurrung burning practices (mosaic burning) managed the landscape sustainably for thousands of years. Why has the loss of this practice contributed to ecological problems?", opts:["Burning was harmful to all species","Without regular low-intensity burns, fuel loads build up, leading to more intense uncontrolled fires that damage ecosystems more severely","Burning always reduces biodiversity","The practice has been maintained unchanged since colonisation"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Which human activity has caused the MOST species extinctions in Australia since 1788?", opts:["Hunting with bows and arrows","Habitat destruction through land clearing, introduced species, and altered fire regimes","Collecting specimens for museums","Pollution alone"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Global warming is causing sea temperatures around Australia to rise. A direct impact on the Great Barrier Reef is:", opts:["Reef fish becoming more abundant","Coral bleaching — corals eject the algae they need for food when too warm and can die","Coral reefs growing faster","No impact on coral reefs"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Which strategy would BEST reduce habitat fragmentation for Victorian wildlife?", opts:["Building more roads","Creating wildlife corridors connecting fragmented bushland patches","Expanding urban areas","Removing all fences"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Overfishing removes too many fish from an ecosystem. The MOST LIKELY consequence is:", opts:["Other species fill the gap with no disruption","Collapse of the food web — predator fish decline, and prey species can explode, disrupting the ecosystem","Fish populations immediately recover","No change to the ecosystem"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"The Yarra River (Birrarung) runs through Wurundjeri Country. Pollution and altered water flows have damaged its health. This affects:", opts:["Only the river itself","The entire catchment ecosystem — all species that depend on the river for water, food, and habitat","Only fish species","Only downstream users"], ans:1 },
  { deck:10, q:"Which of the following is an example of SUSTAINABLE land use?", opts:["Clearing all native vegetation for crops","Rotating crops, maintaining native buffer strips, and reducing pesticide use","Draining all wetlands for farming","Paving over natural ground for car parks"], ans:1 },

  /* ── DECK 11: Conservation & Action ────────────────────────── */
  { deck:11, q:"What does CONSERVATION mean in an ecological context?", opts:["Locking all land away from human use","The protection, management, and restoration of ecosystems and species to maintain biodiversity","Only protecting individual animals","The study of extinct species"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"What is the purpose of a national park?", opts:["To provide land for farming","To protect ecosystems, maintain biodiversity, and allow sustainable recreation","To develop mining operations","To house all endangered animals"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Which Australian law lists threatened species and protects their habitats?", opts:["The Clean Air Act","The Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act (EPBC Act)","The Mining Act","The Animals Act"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"The IUCN Red List categorises species by extinction risk. Which category represents the HIGHEST risk of extinction?", opts:["Least Concern","Near Threatened","Vulnerable","Critically Endangered"], ans:3 },
  { deck:11, q:"Which of the following is an example of an active conservation strategy?", opts:["Ignoring threatened species","Captive breeding programs for endangered species like the eastern barred bandicoot","Banning all scientific study","Removing all apex predators"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Citizen science programs like iNaturalist allow the public to:", opts:["Replace professional scientists","Report and document species, contributing data that helps monitor biodiversity","Only study plants","Earn money for conservation work"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Wurundjeri-Woiwurrung people have been caring for Country on the Yarra River (Birrarung) for thousands of years. Their conservation practices include:", opts:["Introducing new species from other continents","Seasonal burning, sustainable harvesting, and movement that allowed ecosystems to recover","Permanently fencing off all land","Removing all apex predators"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Why is it important to involve First Nations people in conservation planning?", opts:["Only because it is legally required","Because they hold thousands of years of ecological knowledge about local species, relationships, and management practices","Because they must build all fences","Because scientists cannot work without their permission"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"What is 'rewilding'?", opts:["Releasing pets into the wild","Restoring ecosystems by reintroducing species that have been lost, allowing natural processes to resume","Farming native animals","Removing all introduced species permanently"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Wildlife corridors help conservation because they:", opts:["Attract tourists","Allow animals to move between fragmented habitat patches, enabling gene flow and population recovery","Replace national parks","Are only useful for birds"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"The eastern barred bandicoot was declared extinct in the wild in Victoria. Conservation efforts at Healesville Sanctuary have helped to:", opts:["Confirm its global extinction","Breed bandicoots in captivity and reintroduce them to fenced, predator-free reserves","Move all bandicoots overseas","Show that captive breeding does not work"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Which of the following is something a Year 7 student could do to support biodiversity in their local area?", opts:["Clear all introduced plants with chemicals","Plant native species in their garden, reduce pesticide use, and participate in citizen science","Do nothing — only governments can help","Remove all insects from the garden"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Traditional Wurundjeri mosaic burning creates a patchwork of different vegetation ages. Why does this increase biodiversity?", opts:["Old-growth forest is always better","Different species use different vegetation stages — some need open grassland, others need dense scrub","Burning removes all competitors","Fire attracts only introduced species"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"What is the purpose of a 'seed bank' in conservation?", opts:["To store seeds for food","To preserve the genetic diversity of plant species so they can be reintroduced if lost from the wild","To study how seeds germinate","To provide seeds for agriculture only"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Conservation of a single species (like the Leadbeater's possum) often protects:", opts:["Only that one species","The entire ecosystem it lives in, because saving its habitat benefits all other species in that ecosystem","Only tree species","Only other possums"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"The Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) is an international agreement that commits countries to:", opts:["Allowing all development projects","Protecting biodiversity, using biological resources sustainably, and sharing benefits fairly","Banning all tourism","Restricting scientific research"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"A school creates a native garden with local plant species. Which ecosystem service does this MOST directly support?", opts:["Water desalination","Habitat and food provision for local insects, birds, and other wildlife — supporting local biodiversity","Timber production","Mining"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Caring for Country, as practised by Wurundjeri-Woiwurrung people, is best described as:", opts:["A form of land ownership","A spiritual and practical responsibility to maintain the health of ecosystems, relationships between species, and the wellbeing of Country","A recent conservation invention","A tourist experience only"], ans:1 },
  { deck:11, q:"Which statement best summarises why biodiversity conservation matters?", opts:["Biodiversity is only important for aesthetic reasons","Biodiversity underpins the ecosystem services all life depends on — food, clean water, climate regulation, and cultural wellbeing","Only endangered species need protection","Conservation is only necessary in tropical countries"], ans:1 }

